<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Taxon classification Animalia Hymenoptera Cynipidae</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia</taxonomicName>
has a dorsally wide pronotum, a character shared with members of the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" rank="tribe" tribe="Synergini">Synergini</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" rank="tribe" tribe="Aylacini">Aylacini</taxonomicName>
(especially some species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Phanacis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phanacis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phanacis</taxonomicName>
). However, the presence of only two prominent teeth on the right mandible and a parascutal carina that extends anteriorly all the way to the notaulus separate 
<taxonomicName authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia scolopiae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scolopiae">Qwaqwaia scolopiae</taxonomicName>
from species of these two tribes (
<bibRefCitation author="Liljeblad, J" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="154" pageNumber="155" pagination="35 - 52" title="Adding another piece to the cynipoid puzzle: the description of a new tribe, genus and species of gall wasp (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae) endemic to The Republic of South Africa." volume="2806" year="2011">Liljeblad et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia</taxonomicName>
has a strong, sharp occipital carina, which distinguishes this genus from both other Afrotropical representatives of this family where the carina is absent. Marginal cell of forewing closed, with veins heavily pigmented, a character state shared with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
, however, the areolet is elongate rhomboidal whereas it is triangular in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
. The hypopygium is short, abrupt, without a projecting ventral spine (present in both other genera), with dense setae forming an apical tuft.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Figure 4. 
<taxonomicName authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia scolopiae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scolopiae">Qwaqwaia scolopiae</taxonomicName>
female (Holotype, South Africa). A habitus lateral view B head and mesosoma dorsal view C head, anterior view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Gall inducer on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Scolopia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Scolopia mundii" order="Malpighiales" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mundii">Scolopia mundii</taxonomicName>
(Eckl. &amp; Zeyh.) Warb. (
<taxonomicName family="Salicaceae" genus="Cynipoidea" lsidName="Cynipoidea" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" rank="family">Salicaceae</taxonomicName>
), a tree in the eudicot subclass 
<taxonomicName family="Rosidae" lsidName="" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" rank="subclass" subclass="Rosidae">Rosidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Liljeblad, J" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="154" pageNumber="155" pagination="35 - 52" title="Adding another piece to the cynipoid puzzle: the description of a new tribe, genus and species of gall wasp (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae) endemic to The Republic of South Africa." volume="2806" year="2011">Liljeblad et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="17">South Africa: Kwazulu-Natal; Mpumalanga.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
